s raised troubling questions about the relationship between nationhood, nationality, and foreign connection. Blending the histories of foreign relations, capitalism, nation-formation, and transnational connection, Stephen Tuffnell compellingly demonstrates that the United States’ struggle toward independent nationhood was entangled at every step with the world’s most powerful empire. With deep research and vivid detail, Made in Britain uncovers this hidden story and presents a bold new perspective on the nineteenth-century cross-Atlantic relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmericanszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Americas (North, Central, South, West Indies).2bisacsh  aamerican association.  aamerican colony.  aamerican history.  aanglophile.  aatlantic capitalism.  aatlantic relations.  abritannia.  abritish american culture.  abritish empire.  abritish history.  acivil war.  adiplomacy.  aemigration.  agottingen flag.  agreat exhibition 1851.  aharpers weekly.  ahistory.  aimmigration.  aimperialism.  ainternational relations.  ajohn bull.  aliverpool.  alondon.  anation building.  anationalism.  anationality.  anationhood.  anonfiction.  aphilanthropy.  apublic diplomacy.  apunch.  aslavery.  atransatlantic.  auncle sam.  avanity fair.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Comple